story.title: Kidnapped - Episode 1
story.storyDescription: Cassie: You have to help me.
story.creator: web-uploader

messages.text: You have to help me.
You’re never up this late. What’s going on?
Call 9-1-1. I’ve been kidnapped.
Are you serious? Where are you?
I’m not joking. I don’t know where I am! Call 9-1-1!
Hold on. I’m calling them now.
Hurry!
1 minute later
Okay, I’m on my house phone with them. They need to know where you are.
I said I don’t know! I’m in a cage with a cement floor.
I’m cold. There’s nothing in here with me.
Can you call them? They can try to triangulate your signal.
No. I tried. I don’t have enough reception. I can only text.
Okay, they said look around. Is there anything you can describe? Like the building or something?
I can’t see anything but the cage. It’s too dark.
What about the person who kidnapped you?
Did you see him?
No. He hit me from behind. Then I woke up here.
Where were you? What time was it?
The cops are going to see if they can find some witnesses, someone that saw something.
I was on Market Street, around eleven, I think.
I was on my way back to my car after dinner with Chad.
Do you think he saw anything?
No. I had to park really far away from the restaurant.
Were you being followed? Did you notice anything out of the ordinary?
I was hit on the back of the head!
Oh, God, I hear footsteps!
several seconds later
Are you there? Cass?
Are you still there? OMG. Where are you?
I’m still here. I thought I heard footsteps.
Soph, you’ve got to get the police to help me.
They’re trying. They’re asking about your car. You drove the Mustang, right?
No, I had my mom’s car. Red Subaru.
It should still be parked three blocks over, in front of Noisy Oyster. That little side street.
Okay, I’m telling them now. They’re asking if you can hear anything around you. A train? Cars?
Anything can help, Cass. You have to listen hard.
I hear water. It’s dripping behind me somewhere.
It smells in here, like maybe I’m in a sewer or pipes, like a water line.
That could help, right?
I think so. They’ll do something like the guys do on NCIS. Remember?
We watched them save a girl who’d been kidnapped just like this.
It wasn’t like this. That girl could call.
The cops are going to talk to anyone who’s still downtown by your car.
Do you know anything about the person who took you?
It’s a guy. He wore a ski mask when I saw him.
What about accent? Skin color?
Come on, Cass. You’ve got to give them something.
Don’t you think I’m trying?
I’m in a cage, Sophia! I’m scared.
I don’t know where I am or if I’m ever going to see you or my parents again.
Oh, God. My parents. Don’t tell them anything. I don’t want them to worry.
It’s okay. Keep breathing. And I won’t say anything to your parents.
I think his hands were red.
Red? How could his hands be red?
Like really sunburned. Or chapped.
It was dark, but they were dry when they touched me.
Then he said he’d be back. He has a southern accent. It was heavy.
Do you remember anything else?
He has a truck!
I remember now — I woke up for a few seconds and was in the back of a pickup truck.
My hands and feet were tied with rope.
I remember smelling gas. It was so thick it made me cough.
All of this information is going to the police. They’re going to find you. I know they will!
He left my phone with me. Why would he do that?
He has to know I’d try to call for help. Why would he leave me a phone?
You can’t get hysterical right now. You’re the only one who can give us information.
Try to stay calm and focus on what’s important.
No, this is important. He knows I’d call someone.
He WANTS me to call someone.
But why? Oh, God, what did I do?
You’re not making sense. You have no way of knowing what he’s thinking.
The police are telling me that you should breathe and try to remain calm.
What type of lock is on the cage?
Do you have anything you could use to try to pick it?
It’s a chain. I can’t see the lock.
This isn’t right. None of this is right. I shouldn’t have texted you.
He’s going to know.
You’re panicking. Take some deep breaths. The cops are working on this.
No, no, no. He left me the phone for a reason. It could be important.
It’s not important! Getting you out of there is what’s important.
He’s coming! I hear him.
Cassie?
Cassie, where are you?
Are you there? Answer me!
Cassie isn’t available right now. Poor thing was so tired, she needed a nap.
Who is this? What have you done to her?
OMG, don’t hurt her!
Now, now. Cassie’s my property. She’s the beginning of my collection.
I just wanted her to show me who her BFF was. It’ll be nice if her body isn’t here alone.
The police are going to find you! I’m talking to them right now!
Good. Tell them you’re the next piece to my collection. I’ll add you soon.
Cassie will be so happy to have a friend with her.
Sophia screams into the phone. The 9-1-1 operator asks her questions, but she can’t stop shrieking.
I’ll see you soon.
Don’t worry…I’ll take good care of you…
Missing persons report update for Cassandra Ovington, Female, 26.
Ovington was reported missing by her friend, Sophia Venga, Female, 26, on the night of 8/1/18 via a 911 call.
After Venga’s line of communication abruptly ended, police were able to triangulate Ovington’s cell phone.
The bodies of Ovington and Venga were discovered 8/2/18 in a city sewer system, under Blake Street and Vine Avenue.
Police believe the suspect used Ovington’s cell phone contacts and advanced mobile triangulation to locate Venga.
The suspect is still at large.
